Identity theft occurs when someone hijacks a consumer's personal identifying information such as a name, address, credit card or Social Security number and uses the information to open new charge accounts or purchase merchandise.
Under the new law, a conviction for identity theft carries a maximum 15 years jail sentence, a fine and forfeiture of any personal property used to commit the crime.
``I don't think you should have to pay for your own privacy or pay for your own identity theft protection,'' said Ed Mierzwinski, consumer program director at the Public Interest Research Group in Washington.
